english:
  title: On the Marketplaces
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Merchants gather where goods are exchanged—this is called a marketplace. When I first came to the capital and walked through the alleyways, I saw those who paint their faces and peddle seduction, raising and lowering their prices according to beauty and plainness, conducting this business openly without the slightest shame. This I call the Women's Marketplace, and by it I know our customs have grown ugly.

    When I entered the government offices, I saw those who juggle words and mock the law, raising and lowering their fees according to the weight of charges, brazenly accepting payment without hesitation or fear. This I call the Officials' Marketplace, and by it I know our justice has fallen into disorder.

    Now I have witnessed another marketplace arise. Since last year's floods and droughts left the people without sustenance, the strong have turned to banditry and the weak have become beggars, with no means to fill their bellies. Parents sell their children, husbands sell their wives, masters sell their servants. They line the streets, priced cheaply, treated worse than dogs or swine. Yet those in charge turn a blind eye.

    Alas, the first two marketplaces are repugnant in their nature and must be punished severely. The third marketplace, though pitiful in its circumstances, must also be ended swiftly. If these three marketplaces are not abolished, I fear that the ugliness and disorder will only spread further and take deeper root.
  footnotes:
    - Lee Gok (李穀, 1298-1351) was a prominent Goryeo scholar-official known for his moral essays criticizing social ills.
    - 'The ''marketplace'' metaphor represents different forms of corruption: sexual commerce, judicial corruption, and human trafficking born from famine.'
    - The comparison to 'dogs and swine' emphasizes the dehumanizing nature of treating people as commodities.
